docs.abstract: The meeting let North American leaders present a united front without going into detail on deeper issues, including trade disputes or migration.
docs.snippet: The meeting let North American leaders present a united front without going into detail on deeper issues, including trade disputes or migration.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Biden hosted Prime Minister Justin Trudeau of Canada and President Andrés Manuel López Obrador of Mexico at the White House on Thursday, a diplomatic mission that saw three leaders trying to project a united front amid trade scuffles, accusations of American protectionism and ongoing concerns over surging migration at the U.S.-Mexico border.

headline.main: At Summit, U.S., Canada and Mexico Avoid Thorny Questions
headline.print_headline: U.S., Canada and Mexico Push Thornier Issues Aside

byline.original: By Katie Rogers and Natalie Kitroeff

docs.abstract: Journalist groups denounced the arrest of a photographer and a filmmaker covering an Indigenous pipeline protest in British Columbia.
docs.snippet: Journalist groups denounced the arrest of a photographer and a filmmaker covering an Indigenous pipeline protest in British Columbia.
docs.lead_paragraph: OTTAWA — Two journalists arrested at an Indigenous protest against a pipeline last week in western Canada were released Monday on bail, but journalism groups in the country condemned the decision to continue with contempt charges against them.

headline.main: 2 Canadian Journalists Arrested at Indigenous Protest Are Freed on Bail

docs.abstract: Josée Forest-Niesing, a Canadian senator from Ontario, died shortly after she went home from a hospital where she had been treated for Covid-19, Canadian officials said Saturday. She was 56.
docs.lead_paragraph: Josée Forest-Niesing, a Canadian senator from Ontario, died shortly after she went home from a hospital where she had been treated for Covid-19, Canadian officials said Saturday. She was 56.

headline.main: A Canadian senator has died after being hospitalized for Covid.

docs.abstract: The move adds more than 2.8 million young people to those eligible for a shot.
docs.snippet: The move adds more than 2.8 million young people to those eligible for a shot.
docs.lead_paragraph: Canada approved the use of Pfizer-BioNTech’s coronavirus vaccine for children ages 5 to 11 on Friday, adding more than 2.8 million young people to those eligible for a shot.

headline.main: Canada approves the Pfizer vaccine for children ages 5 to 11.

docs.abstract: The Canadian men’s team, which has not been in the World Cup since 1986, is now leading the regional qualifying competition.
docs.snippet: The Canadian men’s team, which has not been in the World Cup since 1986, is now leading the regional qualifying competition.
docs.lead_paragraph: The men’s soccer match between Canada and Mexico at Commonwealth Stadium in Edmonton this week was peak Canada. At minus 9 Celsius with snow piled around the pitch, Canada won 2-1 and rose to the top of the regional qualifying standings for the World Cup.

headline.main: A Cold and Snowy Match Leaves Canada’s Soccer Team in an Unexpected Spot

docs.abstract: As housing prices soar in big cities, the country’s eastern provinces are experiencing a surge in migration. Newcomers are being welcomed, but some locals are wary.
docs.snippet: As housing prices soar in big cities, the country’s eastern provinces are experiencing a surge in migration. Newcomers are being welcomed, but some locals are wary.
docs.lead_paragraph: BONAVISTA, Newfoundland — Only a few years ago in Bonavista, a small and sleepy windswept fishing town in Newfoundland, dozens of pastel-colored heritage homes facing the sea sat dilapidated and empty.

headline.main: Urbanites Flock to Atlantic Canada as Pandemic Blunts Cities’ Appeal
headline.print_headline: In Atlantic Canada, a Tide of ‘Come From Awayers’

docs.abstract: Blamed for flooded fields, damaged roads and the occasional death, the beaver, which has played a seminal role in Canadian history, is now viewed by many as a problem, not a point of national pride.
docs.snippet: Blamed for flooded fields, damaged roads and the occasional death, the beaver, which has played a seminal role in Canadian history, is now viewed by many as a problem, not a point of national pride.
docs.lead_paragraph: ALGONQUIN PROVINCIAL PARK, Ontario — The beaver may be one of Canada’s official national symbols, as iconic as the maple leaf, but Canadians have a love-hate relationship with the creature, with the emphasis for many more on the second emotion.

headline.main: Beaver Dams Mean No Love Lost for Canada’s Emblematic Animal
headline.print_headline: A Furry National Symbol, Too Busy for Its Own Good

docs.abstract: Tracey Deer based “Beans” on her experiences as a child during the 1990 Oka crisis, a confrontation between the Mohawk people and the government.
docs.snippet: Tracey Deer based “Beans” on her experiences as a child during the 1990 Oka crisis, a confrontation between the Mohawk people and the government.
docs.lead_paragraph: Tracey Deer can still remember the sound of rocks hitting the car, her panicked mother’s orders to “Get down!” and the loud smash as a back passenger window shattered, showering glass over her screaming little sister.

headline.main: An Indigenous Canadian Director Channels Traumatic Memories Into Film

docs.abstract: In a prairie city, a young moose on the loose crashed into a children’s classroom, sparking a mix of delight and concern on social media.
docs.snippet: In a prairie city, a young moose on the loose crashed into a children’s classroom, sparking a mix of delight and concern on social media.
docs.lead_paragraph: She was a young moose, not even 2 years old, still getting used to her surroundings, when she took a wrong turn on Thursday and crashed through the window of an elementary school classroom in Saskatoon, in Canada’s central prairie.

headline.main: The Moose Came Marching In, and Stole the Hearts of Canadians

docs.abstract: With the military’s leadership in crisis, a new defense minister adopted a recommendation to remove prosecutorial authority for sexual misconduct cases from the armed forces.
docs.snippet: With the military’s leadership in crisis, a new defense minister adopted a recommendation to remove prosecutorial authority for sexual misconduct cases from the armed forces.
docs.lead_paragraph: OTTAWA — The Canadian military will turn over investigations and prosecutions of sexual misconduct cases to the civilian police and courts, the country’s new defense minister announced Thursday.

headline.main: Canada Turns Over Military Sexual Assault Cases to Civilian Courts
headline.print_headline: Canada Gives Civilian Authorities Jurisdiction in Military Sex Assault Cases

byline.original: By Ian Austen and Jennifer Steinhauer
